    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cf/software-quality-assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/sqa",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "SQA acceptance criteria — Gradation 4",
        "description": "The CFD solver must be under documented version control; all simulation scripts must be traceable to a tagged release; regression test suite must cover at least 90% of solver pathways relevant to hemolysis QoIs; an independent code review must be on record."
      },
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2023 R1 was used under a validated installation qualified per ISO 13485 software lifecycle procedures. The solver version is locked to a tagged release (v23.1.0.376) in the project repository. A regression test suite of 214 cases covering rotating-frame, shear-stress transport, and scalar-transport pathways achieved 97% pass rate. An independent code review by a second analyst confirmed boundary condition setup and UDF implementation for the power-law hemolysis scalar. All SQA artefacts are archived in the project DMS under document ID SQA-VAD-2025-003."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cf/numerical-code-verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/ncv",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Numerical code verification acceptance criteria — Gradation 4",
        "description": "Order-of-accuracy tests must confirm second-order spatial convergence for velocity and pressure on at least two manufactured-solution benchmarks; iterative convergence must reach residuals below 1×10⁻⁶ for all transport equations at each operating point."
      },
      "rationale": "Method of Manufactured Solutions (MMS) tests were executed on a 3D rotating-frame Navier–Stokes configuration. Observed spatial order of accuracy was 1.97 ± 0.04 for velocity magnitude and 1.94 ± 0.06 for pressure, consistent with the nominal second-order scheme. Iterative convergence to residuals ≤ 5×10⁻⁷ was achieved for continuity, momentum, k, and ω equations at all five VAD operating points. A separate steady-state lid-driven cavity benchmark at Re=1000 matched the Ghia et al. reference to within 0.3% on centreline velocity profiles. Code verification artefacts are documented in report NCV-VAD-2025-001."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cf/discretization-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/disc-error",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Discretization error acceptance criteria — Gradation 4",
        "description": "Richardson extrapolation on a minimum three-level mesh sequence must yield a Grid Convergence Index (GCI) below 2% for the hemolysis index QoI at all five operating points; y+ values must be below 1 on all wetted surfaces."
      },
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted: coarse (4.2 M cells), medium (12.1 M cells), and fine (34.8 M cells). Richardson extrapolation yielded GCI values of 0.41–0.87% for the hemolysis index across all five operating points, well below the 2% acceptance threshold. The apparent order of convergence was 1.89, consistent with the second-order discretisation scheme. Wall y+ values ranged from 0.3 to 0.9 on all wetted surfaces. The fine mesh was selected as the production mesh. Discretization error study is documented in report DE-VAD-2025-002, with all mesh files archived."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cf/test-conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/test-conditions",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Test conditions acceptance criteria — Gradation 4",
        "description": "Experimental boundary conditions (flow rate, rotational speed, fluid properties) must be measured with calibrated instruments traceable to NIST standards; measurement uncertainty must be reported for all boundary condition parameters; the five CFD operating points must reproduce the experimental set-points to within instrument uncertainty."
      },
      "rationale": "All experimental test conditions were measured using NIST-traceable instrumentation: Coriolis flow meter (±0.1% FS), torque transducer (±0.05% FS), and calibrated tachometer (±1 RPM). Fluid viscosity and density were measured at 37 °C using a cone-and-plate rheometer and pycnometer respectively. The five CFD operating points were set to match experimental set-points; deviations were less than 0.05 L/min in flow rate and less than 2 RPM in rotational speed — both within instrument uncertainty. Test condition documentation is provided in report TC-VAD-2025-004."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cf/output-comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/output-comparison",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Output comparison acceptance criteria — Gradation 4",
        "description": "Predicted hemolysis index must agree with experimental measurements within combined simulation and experimental uncertainty at all five operating points; normalised root-mean-square error (NRMSE) for velocity profiles must be below 10%; pressure rise must agree within 5%."
      },
      "rationale": "Predicted hemolysis index values agreed with experimental measurements within the combined uncertainty band (simulation U95 + experimental U95) at all five operating points. The maximum point-wise discrepancy was 8.3% at Q=6 L/min / N=2500 RPM, which falls within the combined uncertainty interval. NRMSE for PIV-measured velocity profiles was 6.7% across the impeller mid-plane. Pump pressure rise predictions agreed with measurements to within 3.1% at all operating points. Output comparison metrics are documented in validation report VR-VAD-2025-005."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cf/relevance-qoi",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/relevance-qoi",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "QoI relevance acceptance criteria — Gradation 4",
        "description": "The primary QoI (hemolysis index, NIH) must be directly linked to the clinical endpoint (patient haemolysis); secondary QoIs (velocity magnitude, shear stress, pressure rise) must be demonstrated to be mechanistically coupled to the primary QoI through documented sensitivity analysis."
      },
      "rationale": "The normalised index of haemolysis (NIH) is the direct regulatory QoI specified in FDA guidance for blood-contacting devices and is mechanistically linked to patient haemolysis via the Giersiepen–Wurzinger power-law model. Sensitivity analysis demonstrated that hemolysis index is most sensitive to peak shear stress (Sobol index 0.61) and exposure time (Sobol index 0.28), both of which are computed directly from the CFD velocity field. Pressure rise and velocity magnitude serve as intermediate QoIs that are validated against experiment and that govern shear stress distribution. The QoI hierarchy is documented in report QOI-VAD-2025-006."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cf/relevance-validation-activities",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/relevance-val-activities",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Validation activity relevance acceptance criteria — Gradation 4",
        "description": "Validation experiments must use the same FDA generic pump geometry as the COU model; fluid properties must match within ±5%; operating points must span the full COU operating envelope; validation must be performed at MRL-consistent fidelity (full-scale, blood analogue fluid, physiological temperatures)."
      },
      "rationale": "All validation experiments were performed on the identical FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry used in the COU model, fabricated by the same vendor to the same dimensional tolerances (±0.05 mm). Blood analogue fluid (glycerol–water mixture, viscosity 3.5 ± 0.1 cP at 37 °C) was used in all experiments, matching COU fluid properties within 3%. The five experimental operating points span the full COU operating envelope (Q=3–6 L/min, N=2000–3500 RPM). Experiments were conducted at 37 ± 0.5 °C in a physiologically representative flow loop. Validation relevance assessment is documented in report VRA-VAD-2025-007."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cf/numerical-solver-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/numerical-solver-error",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Numerical solver error acceptance criteria — Gradation 3",
        "description": "Round-off error must be demonstrated to be negligible relative to discretization error; double-precision arithmetic must be used throughout; iterative solver tolerance must be set sufficiently tight that iterative error is less than 1% of the discretization error estimate."
      },
      "rationale": "All simulations were executed in double-precision arithmetic (64-bit IEEE 754), ensuring round-off error at the level of machine epsilon (~2×10⁻¹⁶) is negligible relative to the discretization error estimate (GCI ~0.5%). Iterative convergence was monitored via residual norms and QoI change per iteration; the hemolysis index changed by less than 0.01% between the final 500 iterations, confirming iterative error well below 1% of the discretization error. Algebraic multigrid solver settings are documented in the simulation setup report NSE-VAD-2025-008."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cf/use-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/use-error",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Use error acceptance criteria — Gradation 3",
        "description": "All simulation inputs must be reviewed by a second qualified analyst; boundary condition files must be version-controlled and diff-checked against the test condition report; a documented checklist must be completed and signed prior to each production run."
      },
      "rationale": "A pre-run checklist (document USE-CHK-VAD-2025) was completed and co-signed by the lead analyst and an independent reviewer prior to each of the five production operating point simulations. Boundary condition input files were version-controlled in Git and diff-checked against the experimental test condition report (TC-VAD-2025-004) by the independent reviewer. No discrepancies were identified. The UDF implementing the hemolysis scalar transport equation was reviewed against the published Giersiepen–Wurzinger correlation and confirmed correct. Use error mitigation is documented in report UE-VAD-2025-009."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cf/model-form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/model-form",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Model form acceptance criteria — Gradation 4",
        "description": "The choice of turbulence model and hemolysis correlation must be justified against published literature for rotating blood-contacting devices; a model form sensitivity study comparing at least two turbulence model variants must be documented; the selected model must reproduce experimental velocity profiles with NRMSE below 10%."
      },
      "rationale": "The SST k–ω turbulence model was selected based on its established performance for separated and rotating flows in blood pump literature (Bludszuweit 1995, Apel et al. 2001, Fraser et al. 2011). A model form sensitivity study compared SST k–ω against the realizable k–ε model and the Spalart–Allmaras one-equation model at the Q=5 L/min / N=3000 RPM operating point. SST k–ω achieved the lowest NRMSE against PIV velocity profiles (6.7% vs. 9.1% for realizable k–ε and 11.4% for S–A). The Giersiepen–Wurzinger power-law hemolysis correlation was selected as the regulatory standard for CFD hemolysis prediction in FDA guidance. Model form justification is documented in report MF-VAD-2025-010."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cf/model-inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/model-inputs",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Model inputs acceptance criteria — Gradation 4",
        "description": "All model input parameters (fluid properties, geometry dimensions, boundary condition values, hemolysis correlation coefficients) must be traceable to NIST-calibrated measurements or published reference values; uncertainty ranges must be assigned to all inputs and propagated through Monte Carlo UQ."
      },
      "rationale": "All 14 model input parameters were assigned probability distributions based on calibrated measurements or published reference data: fluid viscosity (Normal, μ=3.5 cP, σ=0.1 cP), fluid density (Normal, μ=1060 kg/m³, σ=5 kg/m³), flow rate (Normal, μ=set-point, σ=0.05 L/min), rotational speed (Normal, μ=set-point, σ=2 RPM), hemolysis correlation exponent α (Uniform, [0.765, 0.785]), and correlation coefficient C (Uniform, [3.62×10⁻⁷, 3.82×10⁻⁷]). All input distributions are documented in the UQ plan (UQ-VAD-2025-011) and are traceable to NIST-calibrated instruments or published literature (Giersiepen et al. 1990). The 1000-sample Monte Carlo propagation is documented in dataset https://uofa.net/morrison/data/monte-carlo-uq-runs-vad."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cf/test-samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/test-samples",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Test samples acceptance criteria — Gradation 3",
        "description": "Experimental hemolysis measurements must include at least three replicate runs per operating point; inter-run variability must be reported as coefficient of variation (CV); CV must be below 15% for all operating points."
      },
      "rationale": "Hemolysis index measurements were performed in triplicate for each of the five operating points using fresh porcine blood (haematocrit 40 ± 2%). Inter-run CV ranged from 4.2% to 11.8% across all operating points, within the 15% acceptance threshold. Plasma-free haemoglobin was quantified by the cyanmethaemoglobin method per ASTM F1841. Sample preparation, storage, and measurement protocols are documented in the experimental report TS-VAD-2025-012. All raw data are archived in the project DMS."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cf/equivalency-input-parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/equivalency-input-parameters",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Equivalency of input parameters acceptance criteria — Gradation 4",
        "description": "CFD boundary conditions must be demonstrated to be equivalent to experimental conditions within measurement uncertainty for all five operating points; any systematic offsets must be quantified and their effect on QoI propagated."
      },
      "rationale": "A formal equivalency assessment compared CFD boundary condition values against experimentally measured conditions for each of the five operating points. Flow rate equivalency: maximum offset 0.03 L/min (within instrument uncertainty of ±0.05 L/min). Rotational speed equivalency: maximum offset 1 RPM (within instrument uncertainty of ±2 RPM). Fluid viscosity equivalency: CFD value 3.50 cP vs. measured 3.48 ± 0.10 cP — within uncertainty. No systematic offsets were identified. Sensitivity analysis confirmed that the observed input equivalency residuals produce less than 0.5% change in predicted hemolysis index. Equivalency assessment is documented in report EIP-VAD-2025-013."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/decision/cou2-vad-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/morrison/org/fda-cdrh-vv40-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "All 13 ASME V&V 40 credibility factors have been assessed with achieved levels meeting or exceeding required levels. The most demanding factors — discretization error (achieved 5, required 4), numerical code verification (achieved 4, required 4), model form (achieved 4, required 4), and model inputs (achieved 4, required 4) — are fully satisfied. Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification (1000 samples) confirms that the 95th-percentile hemolysis index prediction remains below the absolute clinical threshold across all five operating points, with a maximum U95 of ±12% relative to the predicted mean. Sensitivity analysis identified peak shear stress and exposure time as the dominant contributors to hemolysis prediction uncertainty (combined Sobol index 0.89), and the model has been validated against these quantities. The provenance chain is complete from foundational experimental data through mesh generation, solver verification, and validation activities to the final hemolysis index predictions. The decision to accept is grounded in the structured evidence documented across 13 factor assessment reports (SQA-VAD-2025-003 through EIP-VAD-2025-013) and three validation result packages (VR-01, VR-02, VR-03). No weakeners were identified in the structured assessment.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
